Why Pairing?

# 

<span key="538e26a6675c43c1b6ef478111094902"><span offset-key="538e26a6675c43c1b6ef478111094902:0">Why Pairing?</span></span>

## 

<span key="0dcbd02dbca64a5d805f6d9a8b86b6a2"><span offset-key="0dcbd02dbca64a5d805f6d9a8b86b6a2:0">What's Pair Programming?</span></span>

<span key="e98a1c4f3abf43cc8ec9615057207930">**Pair programming**<span offset-key="e98a1c4f3abf43cc8ec9615057207930:1"> is a commonly used practice in the industry. Many companies strongly recommend or require their developers and data scientists to work out problems together as they continuously deliver software.</span></span>

<span key="ad5c91a408f8423fac85d221be805c07"><span offset-key="ad5c91a408f8423fac85d221be805c07:0">Pairing is also a technique directly correlated with Agile development workflows, and its benefits are often seen in the medium to long-term across development teams. Because the benefits of pairing aren't immediate, the practice has uneven adoptionâ€”but it's seen overall as a good thing!</span></span>

<span key="6ad7ad1941744479b7a39e4614967f27"><span offset-key="6ad7ad1941744479b7a39e4614967f27:0">However, we believe in Lambda School Labs that working in pairs directly correlates with your success as a learner, because:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="4a14da8fddce48919041ae240ea75a43"><span offset-key="4a14da8fddce48919041ae240ea75a43:0">Pairing gives you an extra set of eyes on the code you're deliveringâ€”</span>*even*<span offset-key="4a14da8fddce48919041ae240ea75a43:2"> </span>*before you submit a pull-request.*<span offset-key="4a14da8fddce48919041ae240ea75a43:4"> This allows the pair to work through features thoroughly.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="72e59175a9cd45cf838f1e98109b9539"><span offset-key="72e59175a9cd45cf838f1e98109b9539:0">Pairing forces you to talk through your workâ€”a vital skill for any beginner attempting to break into the industry.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="c4f1ecc5b62640a1924b499527d4c039"><span offset-key="c4f1ecc5b62640a1924b499527d4c039:0">Pairing allows you to work slower in the short-term but catch mistakes before shipping them to production.</span></span>

<span key="a12cd379af494799b9df0ec8524a1ac2"><span offset-key="a12cd379af494799b9df0ec8524a1ac2:0">Pairing can be difficult to pull off correctly, and it can even be uncomfortable to have someone else looking over your shoulder while you work. Our hope is that you can benefit from the techniques laid out in this module as we ensure that you pair to ship tickets </span>*at least 3 times*<span offset-key="a12cd379af494799b9df0ec8524a1ac2:2"> throughout your labs journey.</span></span>

<span key="81b81b4d5d114ce4a6fd199289ee57d4"><span offset-key="81b81b4d5d114ce4a6fd199289ee57d4:0"><span slate-zero-width="n">â€‹</span></span></span>

# 

<span key="498a292afca7445d87482ddb9037338a"><span offset-key="498a292afca7445d87482ddb9037338a:0">Pair Programming in Labs</span></span>

<span key="89e29e11779d4446b0adf1adc638f1ee"><span offset-key="89e29e11779d4446b0adf1adc638f1ee:0">It's </span>**required**<span offset-key="89e29e11779d4446b0adf1adc638f1ee:2"> that you pair program to ship the tickets your team scopes for each sprintâ€”</span>*at least*<span offset-key="89e29e11779d4446b0adf1adc638f1ee:4"> 3 occasions throughout your Labs journey. Your experience with these practices is vital to allow you space to articulate your approaches to software development.</span></span>

<span key="2d6491d609d04c4da841cfc529213c1c">**Pairing will force you to talk through the technical tasks at hand and prepare you for interviews by giving you practice talking through your work as an experienced software developer or data scientist.**</span>

<span key="9778ecc155844ce994695d360f2c9269"><span offset-key="9778ecc155844ce994695d360f2c9269:0">In each pull request you make, be sure to document the following:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="87ea734cd346418fa8eac694f4773d1e"><span offset-key="87ea734cd346418fa8eac694f4773d1e:0">Who you paired with</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="4553cd6d5b7d482780e3ef6ec0a9f7cc"><span offset-key="4553cd6d5b7d482780e3ef6ec0a9f7cc:0">What pairing method(s) you used</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="531df92f783341b19d9eaa9de24db8ff"><span offset-key="531df92f783341b19d9eaa9de24db8ff:0">How did it go? What did you learn?</span></span>

# 

<span key="fde45b375d924028ab57a0b77cf81a9a"><span offset-key="fde45b375d924028ab57a0b77cf81a9a:0">How to Pair Program</span></span>

<span key="83f856245ab54b6fbd6b85d0917454b2"><span offset-key="83f856245ab54b6fbd6b85d0917454b2:0">There are a few methods you and your teammates can use to pair program. Try out a few and see how things go naturally as you get better and better at the practice. One of the main principles to live by is "one screen, two devs." In pairing, you always want to be focused on the same screen, same code, same problem together.</span></span>

## 

<span key="330cf427dfcf461894c9c9f63131c061">**Driver & Navigator**</span>

<span key="57e97afdd51742a8b43439088e5d637f"><span offset-key="57e97afdd51742a8b43439088e5d637f:0">The driver and navigator technique is probably the most commonly used. You may apply these "role definitions" however you see fitâ€”and ensure that you switch roles as you see fit. And </span>**don't forget to** </span><a href="https://docs.github.com/en/github/committing-changes-to-your-project/creating-and-editing-commits/creating-a-commit-with-multiple-authors" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="79154407be0e4eb48d0c762c67b09bea" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-32478_259-32479-237__"><span data-key="8a8617c0a6ae42afbdbfd4c2743aa443"><strong>co-author your commits (Links to an external site.)</strong></span></span></a><span key="3f866f8c825a40b39c11dae4a4f5cab6"><span offset-key="3f866f8c825a40b39c11dae4a4f5cab6:0"> so you both get the contributions you deserve.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="31e764a7205a4c97a218439e34199256">**The driver**<span offset-key="31e764a7205a4c97a218439e34199256:1"> in this scenario would have their hands on the keyboard, and in a remote setting will share the screen from which the pair operate. The driver should always be talking through whatever it is they're doing.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="492b76ed16b9460cb0987ae2d3daaacc">**The navigator**<span offset-key="492b76ed16b9460cb0987ae2d3daaacc:1"> sits in the observer's seat as the driver is driving development. This role gives directions as the pair move toward solutions. They confidently debug and fix code on the fly.</span></span>

<span key="e3884925f7c74369b0712a47a91014e6"><span offset-key="e3884925f7c74369b0712a47a91014e6:0">The benefits of the </span>**Driver & Navigator**<span offset-key="e3884925f7c74369b0712a47a91014e6:2"> technique are that it allows the pair to:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="b32598c2a73145c394a7a421f6db8d2d"><span offset-key="b32598c2a73145c394a7a421f6db8d2d:0">apply specific yet different perspectives to the task at hand.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="4a53c7b460cb4184bf63ee5398dae0dd"><span offset-key="4a53c7b460cb4184bf63ee5398dae0dd:0">have one developer (driver) focused on implementing features, while the other (navigator) focuses on the bigger picture of the features being implemented.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="8dfc9e12d8f746fe8411a70dfedf9583"><span offset-key="8dfc9e12d8f746fe8411a70dfedf9583:0">communicate thoughts, ideas, key learnings, and foundational concepts in a clear and concise manner.</span></span>

## 

<span key="837fbb117ce14c03a522497e17bf6e54">**Ping Pong**</span>

<span key="b747206b867341938e54194fa54edef2"><span offset-key="b747206b867341938e54194fa54edef2:0">For those interested in flexing their Test Driven Development (TDD) muscles, the </span>**Ping Pong**<span offset-key="b747206b867341938e54194fa54edef2:2"> method is perfect. If you want to implement features in a test-driven way, then it's recommended you pair using this method.</span></span>

<span key="ac82dc0116954e42b60a59afa2db0918"><span offset-key="ac82dc0116954e42b60a59afa2db0918:0">A common flow for the </span>**Ping Pong**<span offset-key="ac82dc0116954e42b60a59afa2db0918:2"> method can be:</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="0bb48e62e9ff4381b731720972be6f53"><span offset-key="0bb48e62e9ff4381b731720972be6f53:0">Developer A writes a failing test. </span>***Ping!***</span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="7e62dac87ada4d149f289b6485b34940"><span offset-key="7e62dac87ada4d149f289b6485b34940:0">Developer B writes the implementation to make the test pass. </span>***Pong!***</span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="b7395c0353b54a67b4a4ec9063e3024b"><span offset-key="b7395c0353b54a67b4a4ec9063e3024b:0">After each pong, both have a short retrospective where they may refactor the code together and augment the test to reflect the refactor. Now would be a good point to also switch the ping/pong roles.</span></span>

## 

<span key="cf0d2ca8fc2d4234ba9fb17093866d3b">**Strong-Style**</span>

<span key="2c0c6d95b4a04140bd5e31d82c113d06"><span offset-key="2c0c6d95b4a04140bd5e31d82c113d06:0">When one developer is more advanced than the other, this technique helps with that knowledge gap-fill.</span></span>

> <span key="c8ee190c51c945d082da6d9406b11bbf"><span offset-key="c8ee190c51c945d082da6d9406b11bbf:0">The rule: "For an idea to go from your head into the computer, it MUST go through someone else's hands".</span></span>

<span key="c91a3effbe0849868c6e8ffe57424a93"><span offset-key="c91a3effbe0849868c6e8ffe57424a93:0">In this style of pairing, you'll commonly see a </span>**Driver & Navigator**<span offset-key="c91a3effbe0849868c6e8ffe57424a93:2"> setup, with the </span>**navigator**<span offset-key="c91a3effbe0849868c6e8ffe57424a93:4"> being the "</span>***stronger***<span offset-key="c91a3effbe0849868c6e8ffe57424a93:6">" developer of the two.</span></span>

<span key="152ee7cff1454d8aa9f6a6b5d074cdf2"><span offset-key="152ee7cff1454d8aa9f6a6b5d074cdf2:0">As a </span>**driver**<span offset-key="152ee7cff1454d8aa9f6a6b5d074cdf2:2"> in this scenario, be sure that you do your best to learn and understand the knowledge of the stronger developer. You most likely won't be able to grasp everything, so it's ok to attain "partial or incomplete" knowledge. Learn how to become comfortable with having a lack of understanding in the knowledge transfer. Ask questions like, "Why did you choose this technique over xyz?" Stay curious and positiveâ€”and have fun!</span></span>
